<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08070f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08070f">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08070f"> 70(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ <u>M</u>e iij</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Weise goes so far as to say that &lsquo;the Englishman &hellip; writes &hellip; nothing but the beloved <i><b>I</b></i> with a big letter&rsquo; &hellip;. But &hellip; <font color="green">[i]</font>f self-assertion had been the real cause, why should not <i>me</i> also be written <i><b>Me</b></i>? The reason for writing <i>I</i> is &hellip; the orthographic habit in the middle ages of using a &lsquo;long i&rsquo; (that is, <b>j or I</b>), whenever the letter was isolated or formed the last letter of a group; the numeral &lsquo;one&rsquo; was written j or I (and three, <b>iij</b>, etc.) just as much as the pronoun. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 231-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
